<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Know When To Hold Them<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.70)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9038'>Jared "Mister" Stein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9038&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br>
  You got to know when to hold &#39;em,<br>
  Know when to fold &#39;em,<br>
  Know when to walk away,<br>
  Know when to run.<br>
  --Kenny Rogers, &quot;The Gambler&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Author&#39;s Note: This article is intended to be useful players of all skill level, but will be most beneficial to beginner and intermediate level players.<br>
<br>
<br>
My initial strategy to playing LOTR was based on a simple premise: drop anything and everything whenever you can; give the Fellowship something to shoot at, and give your own Fellowship more people to be shot.  I&#39;ve phrased this deliberately to reveal an inherent flaw in this line of thinking: sometimes a minion is played to now effect, sometimes a companion is like a round of Russian Roulette. As I&#39;ve slowly become iniated into more serious LOTR CCG playing, I&#39;ve realized what all the good players know: precalculating outcomes is what can win the game.<br>
<br>
Let me start by addressing the practice of playing minions as soon as they enter your hand. This, in general, is a good strategy because it gives you a chance to (a) clean out your hand to make room for the next turn, and (b) wound the opponent, (c) make use of valuable Shadow Pool.  But how carefully do you consider the opposition before you spend that Shadow Pool that the Free People have so generously granted you? Too many times a battle has ended before it even began. Here are two really simplistic, but all too common, examples:<br>
<br>
The Fellowship just moved to site 3 (a sanctuary). Legolas Greenleaf is there with Frodo, and either Arwen or Aragorn are there to back them up.  They &quot;got lucky&quot; at site 2 so there are less than 2 wounds.  You&#39;ve got a slim but workable Shadow Pool and a few minions.  Should you play your minions? Or hold onto them?<br>
<br>
At this point, the only way it would be worth your while to play your minions is if (a) you can hope to overwhelm one or more characters, or (b) you can hope to dish out more than 4 wounds.  Unless you&#39;ve got some way to drop a dark side miracle on the fellowship, you&#39;d be hard pressed to do either of these in the present, very common, situation. Remember Legoas can exert twice to shoot someone down, and hey that&#39;s no big deal because if he stays put he gets to heal because he&#39;s at a sanctuary.  And anything that survives can probably be blocked by Frodo (who can Stealth out), Aragorn (who is beefy), or Arwen (who is beefy against Nazgul, or is useful as a Ranger, or has one or more nasty elven weapons).<br>
<br>
Now it would be excellent strategy to play some minions that you don&#39;t want in your hand, especially if they will be just as useful in your discard pile (e.g Moria Swarm), or if your own fellowship is so battered that you _need_ some more Free Peoples cards. If your minions survive the battle (Nazgul: probably, Moria: probably not) that will certainly discourage your opponent from moving again, as no one likes to be followed, especially if the alternative is to be healed.<br>
<br>
If none of these reasons apply, you&#39;d be best off holding onto those cards, fixing your hand, and tricking your opponent (who has nearly a full hand and almost no wounds) into thinking that you have nothing playable, that he does not need to rest at the sanctuary, and might as well move on.  If he does make this poor choice you will certainly have more Shadow Pool and, if you fixed your hand right, more cards to throw at him.  Plus you may get to play your site 4, giving you even more of an edge in the upcoming skirmishes.<br>
<br>
Even if you have some brutish, beefy minions to play you need to consider how effective they will be at this time; remember, the easiest way for Shadow to win is to overwhelm the ring bearer. Even if you&#39;ve got the Witch King ready to go deal some damage, it may still be nothing more than a wasted card if you&#39;re not going to overwhelm someone or deal more damage than they can heal.  Card advantage, in this case, has nothing to do with how many you get to draw but more to do with controlling the cards that you have in your hand, weeding out the useless cards but holding onto to the cards that will be most useful at the next site.<br>
<br>
Sometimes you need to think more than one site ahead. If I was Shadow at site 3 and I had the (unlikely) chance to play a Cave Troll or a Witch King I would definitely consider holding on to them until site 5, where you are guaranteed some decent pool, and have the chance to sculpt your hand for a major, single turn beatdown.<br>
<br>
For the Free Peoples side it is often wise to drop as many Free Peoples cards as possible in a turn in order to make room for more Shadow cards, especially with the game the way it is now.  But there are things to consider with this as well.  First, are you going to need those cards at the next site, possibly a site with a huge Shadow number and the potential for some serious smacking? Second, if the card is not immediately useful and you do drop the card to make room, what is the chance that you will draw another copy of that card in the near future? Third, and perhaps most importantly, how much are the cards going to contribute to the Shadow Pool in a meaningful way? By &quot;meaningful way&quot; I mean: if the cards are played during the Fellowship phase is it going to add up to enough for the opponent to play one or more useful minions during the Shadow phase?  If the cards are played during the Manuever, Archery, or Skirmish phases are they going to give the Shadow Pool the chance to play their own Manuever, Archery, or Skirmish events? If you plan to move twice this turn are your cards going to be more useful for you at the next site, particularly if by not playing them now you maintain the Shadow Pool at its current level and prevent the opponent from playing an excessive amount of minions at the next Shadow phase?<br>
<br>
One final element I want to mention that applies to knowing when to hold them on both the Free Peoples and the Shadow side; the rules for Lord of the Rings CCG states: &quot;As the Free People&#39;s player, you get the first opportunity to perform a (Maneuver/Archery/Assignment/Skirmish) action, and then the player on your right gets an opportunity... If a player does not wish to perform a (Maneuver/Archery/Assignment/Skirmish) action, he may simply pass. However, when all players consecutively pass proceed to the (Archery/Assignment/Skirmish) phase (or resolve that skirmish.&quot;<br>
<br>
This rule is very important because it gives the Shadow player an advantage.  If you are the Free Peoples player and you are in a Skirmish, let&#39;s say Aragorn, naked, is up against an Orc Scavenger, also naked.  As it stands Aragorn is going to lose the skirmish and take a wound. Ah, but you have a Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom in your hand and you can play it to win the skirmish.  The only hesitation you may have is that the Shadow player may have a Drums in the Deep in his/her hand to counter your Swordsman, and you would still lose the skirmish.  Should you pass the skirmish action to see if your opponent will play an event? Only if you know your opponent DOES have a strength boosting card in his or her hand. In this case your playing Swordsman would be a waste as you could have held onto that card for a more useful skirmish.  But if you pass hoping that your opponent will play their event first, you are out of luck, for you get the first chance to play an event, and if your opponent, secure with the 10-to-10 pairing, chooses to not play an event the skirmish is over. You do not get a second chance to play your Swordsman if the opponent does not play an event (or use an action).<br>
<br>
As a Shadow player, this is equally important.  Do not let your Free Peoples opponent trick you into playing your event first. If its a 10-to-10 situation like this, let him pass the event action; you can pass and immediately end the skirmish, winning it and assigning a wound.  As a Shadow player I often am asked as soon as the skirmish happens, if I&#39;m going to play an event.  This is, of course, backwards. It should be _me_ asking them.  But whenever I am asked I generally answer, &quot;Not unless you&#39;re going to,&quot; or I prompt them to play an event first.<br>
<br>
The exception to consider is the occasion when, for either player, events in your hand will be rendered useless after this skirmish is over (e.g. if the Cave Troll mit Hammer is going to step on both Legolas and Arwen, and you hold 3 Defiances in your hand. Playing those 3 won&#39;t help your strength enough against damage +2 Troll, but it will clear your hand of useless cards.)<br>
<br>
Card advantage is all about having the cards you need when you need them. Don&#39;t throw good cards away in pointless skirmishes, don&#39;t hold onto powerful events if they won&#39;t be useful in the next turn or two. Following these strategies will help you maximize the usefulness of the cards in your hand, conserve your power, and sculpt your hand for the ultimate efficiency. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3292&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
